title: Claim and deal with Child Benefit for someone else

heading_context: Claim and deal with Child Benefit for someone else
chunks.html_content:
You can claim Child Benefit for a child you’re responsible for and their baby.

If your child is claiming the Child Benefit, you can collect the payment on their behalf by talking to their bank.

The Child Benefit Office can only pay Child Benefit into one account. This can be a joint account you share with your child, but their name must be on the account too.

This guide is also available in Welsh (Cymraeg).

heading_context: Claim and deal with Child Benefit for someone else
chunks.html_content:
You can apply for the right to deal with the Child Benefit of someone who cannot manage their own affairs, for example because they’re mentally incapable or severely disabled.

This is called becoming an ‘appointee’.

You can apply as an individual or as a voluntary organisation.

If you’re paid to deal with someone else’s Child Benefit, you’re known as a ‘paid agent’.

chunks.html_content: You’re not an appointee if you just help someone complete their claim form.

heading_context: Claim and deal with Child Benefit for someone else
How to become an appointee
chunks.html_content: Contact the Child Benefit Office to apply. They’ll discuss if becoming an appointee is the best option and tell you what you need to do.
chunks.plain_content:

heading_context: Claim and deal with Child Benefit for someone else
How to become an appointee
chunks.html_content: You can arrange with someone’s bank or the Post Office to collect their payments without becoming an appointee.
chunks.plain_content:
Claim and deal with Child Benefit for someone else
How to become an appointee
You can arrange with someone’s bank or the Post Office to collect their payments without becoming an appointee.

heading_context: Claim and deal with Child Benefit for someone else
Your responsibilities
chunks.html_content:
As an appointee, you must do things like:

  • complete the claim form
  • deal with any letters from the Child Benefit Office
  • report any changes that affect Child Benefit
  • stop or restart payments where the person or their partner is affected by the High Income Child Benefit Charge

The Child Benefit will be paid into your bank account.

heading_context: Claim and deal with Child Benefit for someone else
Stop or change an appointee or paid agent
chunks.html_content: Write to the Child Benefit Office within one month of when you want to stop or change the appointee.

heading_context: Claim and deal with Child Benefit for someone else
Get authorised
If you act for a lot of clients
chunks.html_content:
The Child Benefit Helpline can only discuss a claim with the person named on the claim form (or their appointee). A partner or someone else can get general advice but they must be ‘authorised’ to discuss a claim with the helpline.

The process is different if you act for a lot of clients or you’re a paid agent.

The claimant must fill in form TC689, or write a letter with the same information, and send it to the Tax Credit Office - the address is on the form.

The authorisation lasts 12 months unless a different end date is put on the form. It usually takes 2 days to get authorised from when your form is received. Usually, you won’t get a letter confirming the authorisation.

The Child Benefit Office will also need to have received the claimant’s Child Benefit claim form.

More than one person can be authorised but they each must send a TC689 form.

Write to the Tax Credit Office to register as an ‘intermediary organisation’ if you work in the voluntary sector and act for many people.

You can get urgent authorisation online if you’re an intermediary organisation and you have a completed TC689. You must keep your client’s completed TC689 for 7 years from the date it was signed.

Get authorised
If you’re a paid agent
chunks.html_content:
Your client must send a letter to the Child Benefit Office, saying you can deal with Child Benefit on their behalf.

To authorise you to deal with High Income Child Benefit Tax Charge matters they also need to fill in form CH995.
